<p>In comparison to the I3 instances, the I3en instances offer:</p> 
<ul> 
 <li>A cost per GB of SSD instance storage that is up to 50% lower</li> 
 <li>Storage density (GB per vCPU) that is roughly 2.6x greater</li> 
 <li>Ratio of network bandwidth to vCPUs that is up to 2.7x greater</li> 
</ul> 
<p>You will need HVM AMIs with the NVMe 1.0e and ENA drivers. You can also make use of the new Elastic Fabric Adapter (EFA) if you are using the <strong>i3en.24xlarge </strong>(read my <a href="https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/now-available-elastic-fabric-adapter-efa-for-tightly-coupled-hpc-workloads/">recent post</a> to learn more).</p> 
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline"><strong>Now Available</strong></span><br /> You can launch I3en instances today in the <span title="">US East (N. Virginia)</span>, <span title="">US West (Oregon)</span>, and <span title="">Europe (Ireland)</span> Regions in On-Demand and Spot form. Reserved Instances, Dedicated Instances, and Dedicated Hosts are available.</p> 
